Uni-Variant visual Analysis¶

In [35]:
import math
def uni_variant_visual_num(data):
    num_cols = data.select_dtypes(include='number').columns
    n = len(num_cols)
    
    cols = 3 
    rows = math.ceil(n / cols)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(cols * 10, rows * 10))

    for i, col in enumerate(num_cols, start=1):
        plt.subplot(rows, cols, i)
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=col,kde=True)
        plt.title(f"Distribution of {col}")
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel("Frequency")
        plt.grid(True)

    # plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

import math
def uni_variant_visual_cat(data):
    num_cols = data.select_dtypes(include='object').columns
    n = len(num_cols)
    
    cols = 3 
    rows = math.ceil(n / cols)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(cols * 10, rows * 10))

    for i, col in enumerate(num_cols, start=1):
        plt.subplot(rows, cols, i)
        sns.countplot(data=data, x=col)
        plt.title(f"Distribution of {col}")
        plt.xlabel(col)
        plt.ylabel("Frequency")
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.legend()
        plt.grid(True)

    plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from itertools import combinations

def plot_bivariate_categorical_bar(df):
    # Step 1: Identify categorical columns
    cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()
    combination = list(combinations(cat_cols, 2))
    
    # Step 2: Prepare subplots
    total = len(combination)
    ncols = 2
    nrows = (total + 1) // ncols
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(15, 5 * nrows))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    # Step 3: Loop through combinations and plot
    for i, (col_x, col_y) in enumerate(combination):
        ct = pd.crosstab(df[col_x], df[col_y])
        ct.plot(kind='bar', ax=axes[i], legend=True)
        axes[i].set_title(f'{col_x} vs {col_y}')
        axes[i].set_xlabel(col_x)
        axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')

    # Hide unused axes
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
plot_bivariate_categorical_bar(df)

In [68]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from itertools import product

def plot_num_vs_cat_boxen(df):
    # Step 1: Select column types
    cat_cols = ['Target']
    num_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns.tolist()
    
    # Step 2: Generate all combinations
    combinations = list(product(num_cols, cat_cols))
    
    # Step 3: Subplot setup
    total = len(combinations)
    ncols = 2
    nrows = (total + 1) // ncols
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(15, 5 * nrows))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    # Step 4: Loop through each (num, cat) and plot boxen
    for i, (num_col, cat_col) in enumerate(combinations):
        sns.boxenplot(data=df, x=cat_col, y=num_col, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f'{num_col} by {cat_col}')
        axes[i].set_xlabel(cat_col)
        axes[i].set_ylabel(num_col)

    # Step 5: Hide extra subplots
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[j])

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
plot_num_vs_cat_boxen(df)

from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler,OrdinalEncoder
ordl=OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['primary','secondary','tertiary','unknown']])
ord2=OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['jan','feb','mar','apr','may','jun','jul','aug','sep','oct','nov','dec']])
colt=ColumnTransformer(transformers=[('t1',MinMaxScaler(),['age','balance','day','duration','campaign','pdays','previous']),('t2',OrdinalEncoder(),['job','marital','default','housing','loan','contact','poutcome']),('t3',ordl,['education']),('t4',ord2,['month'])])
X_transformed=colt.fit_transform(X)
columns=['age','balance','day','duration','campaign','pdays','previous']+['job','marital','default','housing','loan','contact','poutcome']+['education']+['month']
X_transformed=pd.DataFrame(X_transformed,columns=columns)

In [148]:
def tune_models_return_best_only(X, y, models_and_params, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'):
    best_models={}
    for name, mp in models_and_params.items():
        print(f"Tuning {name}...")
        grid = GridSearchCV(mp['model'], mp['params'], cv=cv, scoring=scoring)
        grid.fit(X, y)
        print(f"Best score for {name}: {grid.best_score_:.4f}")
        print(f'Best Parametes for {name} is {grid.best_params_}')
        best_models[name]=grid.best_estimator_
    return best_models

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix,accuracy_score,precision_score,recall_score,f1_score,roc_curve,roc_auc_score,confusion_matrix,classification_report
def performance(best_models,X_test,y_test):
    for name,model in best_models.items():
        print('*'*20,name,'*'*20)
        y_predict=model.predict(X_test)
        print("Accuracy Score:",accuracy_score(y_test,y_predict))
        print("Confusion Matrix\n",confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict))
        print('Classification Report:\n',classification_report(y_test,y_predict))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Assume y_test contains labels like 'yes' and 'no'
# Convert y_test to binary: 'yes' -> 1, 'no' -> 0
y_test_binary = (y_test == 'yes').astype(int)

# Plot ROC curves for each model
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

for name, model in best_models.items():
    # Predict probabilities for the positive class
    y_prob = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

    # Compute False Positive Rate and True Positive Rate
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test_binary, y_prob)
    
    # Compute Area Under the Curve
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test_binary, y_prob)
    
    # Plot the ROC curve
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"{name} (AUC = {auc:.2f})")

# Diagonal reference line
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')

# Plot settings
plt.title("ROC Curves")
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

📊 Model Comparison and Performance Analysis¶

🔹 1. Logistic Regression¶

  • Accuracy: 0.76
  • Precision:
    • No: 0.74
    • Yes: 0.79
  • Recall:
    • No: 0.81
    • Yes: 0.71
  • F1-Score:
    • No: 0.77
    • Yes: 0.75

🧠 Insights:

  • Performs moderately well with a slight bias toward predicting the "no" class (higher recall).
  • Lower recall on "yes" indicates some false negatives.
  • A good baseline model, but other models outperform it significantly.

🔹 2. Decision Tree Classifier¶

  • Accuracy: 0.87
  • Precision & Recall: ~0.87 for both classes
  • F1-Score: 0.87 for both classes

🧠 Insights:

  • Strong and balanced performance for both classes.
  • Easily interpretable and fast.

🔹 3. Random Forest Classifier¶

  • Accuracy: 0.90 (Highest)
  • Precision:
    • No: 0.91
    • Yes: 0.89
  • Recall:
    • No: 0.89
    • Yes: 0.91
  • F1-Score: 0.90 for both classes

🧠 Insights:

  • Best performing model overall.
  • High precision and recall → well-balanced classifier.
  • Less prone to overfitting compared to single trees due to the ensemble method.
  • Suitable for production-level deployment.

🔹 4. Gaussian Naive Bayes¶

  • Accuracy: 0.75
  • Precision & Recall: ~0.74–0.76
  • F1-Score: 0.75

🧠 Insights:

  • Performs similarly to Logistic Regression but slightly worse overall.
  • Assumes feature independence, which may not hold in practice.
  • Lightweight and fast, but not suitable for complex data dependencies.

🔹 5. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)¶

  • Accuracy: 0.875
  • Precision:
    • No: 0.89
    • Yes: 0.86
  • Recall:
    • No: 0.86
    • Yes: 0.89
  • F1-Score: ~0.87–0.88

🧠 Insights:

  • Performs very well, second only to Random Forest.
  • Good at capturing non-linear patterns, but performance depends heavily on k.

Conclusion:¶

  • The Random Forest Classifier performs the best from others with AUC=0.97
  • The KNN with AUC=0.94 and next Decision Tree Classifier with AUC=0.88
